LAGOS – The Federal Operations Unit (FOU), Zone ‘A’, of the Nige­ria Customs Service (NCS), with headquarters in Lagos, has lamented that it lost four of its operatives to the cold hands of death, occasioned by the activities of die-hard smugglers who engaged them in gun battles while trying to evade arrest with smuggled goods. The Unit also disclosed that it arrested 23 suspected smug­glers during the same period. The command, which has averred not to relent in the war against smugglers and economic saboteurs, dis­closed that in the month of January 2022, it continued it’s vigorous anti-smuggling exploits with seizures worth Duty Paid Value(DPV) of N4,590,312,335 and recovered N192,010,155.73 as revenue within five weeks. Fake Soldier, 32 Other Suspects Paraded In Ibadan For Kidnap,… INSECURITY: Nigerian Army Shows Readiness In Partnership With… Acting Controller of the Unit, Deputy Comptroller Hussein Kehinde Ejibunu who disclosed this to Saturday INDEPENDENT, said that four customs officers serving in the unit lost their lives in the course of anti-smuggling activities last year. Ejibunu further disclosed that a total of 23 suspected smugglers were arrested out of which five were given ad­ministrative bail while 18 are in the unit’s custody. He said the unit’s an­ti-smuggling and revenue recovery activities will in­crease this year due to the support and logistics upgrade it received from the Nigeria Customs Service (NCS) Man­agement and Comptroller General of Customs, Col Ha­meed Ibrahim Ali(Rtd). DC Ejibunu, who con­demned the murderous acts of killing customs officers by smugglers and their sym­pathisers also said the long arms of the law would not spare perpetrators of such killings and that the unit will not be deterred in the perfor­mance of its duties to Nigeria. Giving a breakdown of the seizures, Ejibunu said that 9,697 bags of 50kg each, 3,173 cartons of basmati rice at 5kg each and 297 bags (25kg) foreign parboiled rice were seized.